{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4f05c763-569f-41d5-9800-9b58a94c1af1","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\n(Or point to a built DLL: command `dotnet`, args `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`)\n\n**3. Connect & test:**\n\n- Click **Connect** — the Inspector spawns your server as a child process over stdin/stdout.\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list and invoke your tools with sample inputs.\n- Use the **Resources** / **Prompts** tabs if you expose those.\n- Watch the **request/response log** pane for raw JSON-RPC messages.\n\n**⚠️ Important:** Your server must write MCP JSON-RPC messages to **stdout only**. Any stray `Console.WriteLine` / logging to stdout will corrupt the protocol. Send logs to **stderr** instead, or use the MCP `logging/message` notification.\n\n**Tip:** You can also set environment variables in the Inspector UI if your server needs config (e.g., API keys, connection strings).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"351caf7f-80f0-4527-9134-4f48c80b1d49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":402,"requestId":"3C06:2310B5:202924B:2410194:69E81D00"},"id":"54d06d51-b827-48d4-ad1f-23c883d7b017","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:57:47.163Z","parentId":"f961f175-579c-473a-93bd-ddc76dc39d5a"}
